1.Briefly describe the data set. What information does it contain?

This avocado dataset contains a wide range of information about weekly avocado sales across different U.S. regions. The data includes the average retail price of avocados sold, the total sales volume, and counts for different avocado sizes based on PLU codes. It also provides details such as region, year, type (conventional or organic), and the number of avocados sold in various bag sizes. The output above displays the data types and the first few rows of the dataset, giving a clear view of how the original data is structured.

avg_sp_organic_df = avg_sp_organic.to_frame(name="avg_price_organic").reset_index()

  1. The following plot shows, for all four California regions, the proportion of the average Hass avocado sales that are small, large, or extra large; conventional vs.organic. Recreate the plot; you do not have to replicate the exact finishing touches - e.g., color, theme - but your plot should resemble the content of this plot.
Code 
#Keeping only the columns we need to create the visualization
avocado_california = avocado_california[["geography", "type","small_avocado","large_avocado","xlarge_avocado"]]
Code 
# Creating three new columns with the mean avocado sale volume for each size avocado.
avocado_california["avg_small"] = avocado_california.groupby(
    ["geography", "type"]
)["small_avocado"].transform("mean")

avocado_california["avg_large"] = avocado_california.groupby(
    ["geography", "type"]
)["large_avocado"].transform("mean")

avocado_california["avg_xlarge"] = avocado_california.groupby(
    ["geography", "type"]
)["xlarge_avocado"].transform("mean")
Code 
#Creating a total average volume column by adding each size value together.
avocado_california["total_avg_volume"] = (
    avocado_california["avg_small"]
    + avocado_california["avg_large"]
    + avocado_california["avg_xlarge"]
)
Code 
#Creating columns for the proportion of each size of avocado sale volume to the total sale volume
avocado_california["small"] = (
    avocado_california["avg_small"] / avocado_california["total_avg_volume"]
)
avocado_california["large"] = (
    avocado_california["avg_large"] / avocado_california["total_avg_volume"]
)
avocado_california["xlarge"] = (
    avocado_california["avg_xlarge"] / avocado_california["total_avg_volume"]
)
Code 
#Asked chat what the best way to make it so only one record of each cities ratio for both conventional and organic.
avocado_california = avocado_california.drop_duplicates(subset=["geography", "type"])
Code 
# Changed the dataset to have one size and proportion column for all sizes. 
avocado_california = avocado_california.melt(
    id_vars=["geography", "type"],
    value_vars=["small", "large", "xlarge"],
    var_name="size",
    value_name="proportion"
)

# Plot initially had the bars stacked in a strange order so I asked if there was a function to ensure that the bars go from small > large > xlarge.
avocado_california["size"] = pd.Categorical(
    avocado_california["size"],
    categories=["xlarge", "large", "small"],
    ordered=True
)
